social_posts.post_text: LIVE FOREVER —  DECEMBER 2

Live Forever was the culmination of a good year for Gus.  It showcases a variety of talented producers he worked with and provides a beautiful example the sound he was working to create—the sound of “Early Peep.”  It is a strong and definite sound, a sound that is sure of itself in the way Gus had come to be by the time he made Live Forever.  Some of the producers had created beats that Gus asked to use.  Other producers were asked by Gus to sample specific songs.  Gus had a special desire for “Climbing Up The Walls” by Radiohead and asked two of his go-to producers if they would sample that song in a beat for him. Soon after, Fleance created the instrumental for “Pick Me Up.” On Tuesday of this week, @ThomYorke & @radiohead were gracious enough to approve the use of “Climbing Up The Walls” in “Pick Me Up” and allow us to release Live Forever in its entirety.

Gus carefully arranged the songs in a very specific order for this mixtape, even though four of them were created and added within 24 hours of Live Forever’s release.  He knew just what he wanted, and had developed an efficient way to create his music—singing over the beats in the middle of the night so no one could hear him (though I did and pretended not to if he asked).

This is a shining piece of work—made by a boy in his bedroom who had turned 19 on November 1, 2015. Thanks to all of the sampled artists, Gus’s producers, and features that had a role in making this release happen.

Today, Gus’s music came home.

From this day forward, his music will be in the care of his mother and brother, and no one else.
 
It is a solemn moment for us as we reflect on the struggles of the past five plus years.  We are grateful to all of the fans, friends, professionals, and family who stood by us.  We were all permanently changed by Gus’s death.  We know he should be here in the world with all of us, creating--making whatever he was inspired to make.  But he is not.  So, we will protect his music with all of our strength.

We look forward to continuing to release Gus’s music.
 
This is a very important day for us.

Changes was released on May 31, 2016.  However, Gus had worked on the songs he appeared on several months before that.  The first song Gus collaborated with @meetingbychance on was This Feeling.  He finished it the same night he made mirror, mirror from Live Forever. The next five MBC songs were made in December and January, at the same time Gus was working with Jay Grxxn, Ghostemane, Craig Xen, and Nedarb (on such projects as California Girls and Vertigo).  It is hard to imagine someone who could compose so many different songs with so many different collaborators in such a short time, but that had become Gus’s approach to making music.  We are very grateful to Meeting by Chance for working with us to re-release these beautiful songs on their anniversary—seven years later.

To celebrate Crybaby’s 7 year anniversary, we are finally releasing it on vinyl for the first time ever exclusively. You will find it on lilpeep.com.  We have also made all-white cassettes and CDs, if you like those.

Gus was very proud of this body of work.  He created it at a time of excitement and anticipation in his life.

Oskar and I appreciate the patience of Gus‘s fans as we have all waited to release this music on vinyl.

Gus and Makonnen completed the final songs to an album that would later be known as “DIAMONDS” in Los Angeles, 6 years ago, during the late summer of 2017.

Gus was absolutely thrilled about working with Makonnen. When he came home in August, he played those songs for us—over and over.  Gus was incredibly proud of those songs.

While Gus was glad to be home for his grandpa’s birthday, he could not wait to get back to making music with Makonnen.  He knew there was more music to make, and he knew he had limited time due to his upcoming fall COWYS tour, so he organized his next chunk of studio time so he could meet Makonnen in London, where they made the last batch of songs.

We all waited with anticipation the release of this album.  Then Gus died.  I knew I had to do everything I could to help get this album released.

I am very grateful to Makonnen not only for his patience, grace, and fortitude, but also for the tenderness with which he re-assembled the original “Diamonds Team” to gently prepare the album for its release.  He did an amazing job—they all did.  

Gus would be so proud to know that this album had come out.  He would be grateful to his friends for taking the time and care to do it just right.

To celebrate HELLBOY’s 7th anniversary, we are pleased to announce that it is now available on vinyl, CD, and cassette for the first time ever.  Orders are open now on lilpeep.com, and will be available at US and international retailers in the coming weeks.

Star Shopping has just surpassed 1 billion streams on Spotify. Gus made Star Shopping mid-August, 2015 after getting home from celebrating his grandfather’s 78th birthday. It is amazing to consider the fact that he made such a beautiful song so simply—using a beat a friend of his from the Internet had given him, a pair of $200 headphones, my old MacBook Pro and GarageBand.  He had no label, no studio, no promo. He worked alone in his bedroom, usually throughout the night.  The success of this song is testimony to his gift as a poet, his passion, his honesty, and the way he used his voice to evoke feelings in all of us.

To celebrate Gus’s 27th birthday, Oskar and I asked @overallmurals to paint another mural and they did an amazing job. Special thanks to @jasperpatch and @metzxart for their beautiful artistry and to @mmainenti for documenting their work for us. You can see this mural in person at 29 Wyckoff Ave, on the corner of Wyckoff Ave and Troutman street in Bushwick, Brooklyn. Special thank you also to @yoshinostudios for taking the photograph that served as the reference for this painting. If you come on November 1, Gus’s birthday, we will be doing something special in the neighborhood…

We are proud to be able to release COWYS Pt. 2 in its original form. After several extensive conversations with Smokeasac, we learned about Gus’s original plans for COWYS in 2017 when he had to split the whole mixtape into two parts. We are very proud to understand what Gus had intended, and even prouder to be able to execute that vision on his behalf. These songs were exported directly from Gus’s GarageBand sessions on his computer in the highest audio quality possible.  Thank you to the producers who have educated us on this journey. I encourage Gus’s fans to enjoy the music that Gus created, listened to, and loved. Thank you to the PeeP team that made it happen.
